<subsection xml:id="subsec-similarity">
    <title>Similarity</title>

    <p>
        Similarity refers to a relationship between two shapes or figures where one can be transformed into the other through scaling (enlargement or reduction), without changing its shape. 
        The two shapes are similar if they have the same shape but may differ in size.
    </p>

    <activity>
        <statement>
            <p>
                 <m>{\color{blue} \text{Work in groups.}}</m>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </activity>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                In figure below, the triangles <m>PQR</m> and <m>ABC</m> are similar. Calculate the lengths marked with letter <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>.
            </p>

            <sidebyside>
                <image>
                    <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                    <latex-image label="similar-triangle1">
                        \begin{tikzpicture}
                            % Draw and fill the triangle
                            \fill[blue!30] (0,0) -- (2,0) -- (1,2) -- cycle;
                            \draw[blue, thick] (0,0) -- (2,0) -- (1,2) -- cycle;
                            
                            % Label vertices
                            \node[left] at (0,0) {\textbf{A}};
                            \node[right] at (2,0) {\textbf{B}};
                            \node[above] at (1,2) {\textbf{C}};
                            
                            % Label midpoints with segment lengths
                            \node[below] at (1,0) {\textbf{6 cm}};
                            \node[left] at (0.5,1) {\textbf{9 cm}};
                            \node[right] at (1.5,1) {\textbf{x }};
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                    
                </image>

                <image>
                    <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                    <latex-image label="similar-triangle2">
                        \begin{tikzpicture}
                             % triangle (red) with labels
                            \fill[red!30] (3,0) -- (6,0) -- (4.5,3) -- cycle;
                            \draw[red, thick] (3,0) -- (6,0) -- (4.5,3) -- cycle;
                            
                            % Label vertices for second triangle
                            \node[left] at (3,0) {\textbf{P}};
                            \node[right] at (6,0) {\textbf{Q}};
                            \node[above] at (4.5,3) {\textbf{R}};
                            
                            % Label midpoints with segment lengths (second triangle)
                            \node[below] at (4.5,0) {\textbf{y }};
                            \node[left] at (3.75,1.5) {\textbf{12 cm}};
                            \node[right] at (5.25,1.5) {\textbf{14 cm}};
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                    
                </image>
            </sidebyside>
        </statement>

        <solution>
            <p>
                <m>AB</m> corresponds to <m>PQ</m>, <m>BC</m> corresponds to <m>QR</m>, and <m>AC</m> corresponds to <m>PR</m>.
            </p>

            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>\text{Therefore,} \amp \frac{AB}{PQ}= \frac{AC}{PR}= \frac {BC}{QR} </mrow>
                    <mrow> =\amp \frac{6\, cm}{y}= \frac{9\, cm}{12\, cm}= \frac {x}{14\, cm} </mrow>
                    <mrow> \frac{6\, cm}{y}=\amp \frac{9\, cm}{12\, cm}</mrow>
                    <mrow> y \times 9\, cm= \amp 6\, cm \times 12\, cm </mrow>
                    <mrow> y= \amp \frac{108\, cm^2}{9\, cm}  </mrow>
                    <mrow> y =\amp 12\, cm </mrow>
                    <mrow>\text{Therefore PQ}= \amp 12 cm</mrow>
                     <mrow> \frac{9\, cm}{12\, cm}=\amp \frac{x}{14\, cm}</mrow>
                    <mrow> x \times 12\, cm= \amp 9\, cm \times 14\, cm </mrow>
                    <mrow> x= \amp \frac{126\, cm^2}{12\, cm}  </mrow>
                    <mrow> y =\amp 10.5\, cm </mrow>
                    <mrow>\text{Therefore BC}= \amp 10.5\, cm</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Given that triangles <m>XYZ</m> and <m>PQR</m> in the figure below are similar, Find the size of <m>\angle\, QPR</m>, <m>\angle\, PQR</m> and the length of line <m>PR</m>
            </p>

            <figure xml:id="triangle-xyz">
                <caption></caption>
            <image>
                <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                <latex-image label="triangle-xyz">
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                        % Triangle ABC (Blue fill)
                        \fill[blue!30] (0,0) -- (5,0) -- (2,3.5) -- cycle;  % Light blue fill
                        \draw[thick, blue] (0,0) -- (5,0) -- (2,3.5) -- cycle;
                        
                        % Labels for triangle ABC
                        \node[left] at (0,0) {Y};
                        \node[right] at (5,0) {Z};
                        \node[above] at (2,3.5) {X};
                        \node[below] at (2.5,0) {16 cm};
                        \node[left] at (1,2) {12 cm};
                        \node[right] at (3.5,2) {14 cm};

                        % Angles
                        \draw[thick] (0.8,0) arc[start angle=0,end angle=59,radius=0.8cm];
                        \node at (1.2,0.3) {\small $72^\circ$};

                        \draw[thick] (4.2,0) arc[start angle=180,end angle=131,radius=0.8cm];
                        \node at (3.8,0.3) {\small $61^\circ$};

                        % Triangle PQR (Red fill)
                        \fill[red!30] (8,0) -- (14,0) -- (11,4) -- cycle; % Light red fill
                        \draw[thick, red] (8,0) -- (14,0) -- (11,4) -- cycle;
                        
                        % Labels for triangle PQR
                        \node[left] at (8,0) {P};
                        \node[right] at (14,0) {Q};
                        \node[above] at (11,4) {R};
                        \node[below] at (11,0) {40 cm};
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
            </image>

          </figure>

            
        </statement>

        <solution>
            <p>
                Since the two triangles are equal, then their corresponding angles must be equal 
            </p>

            <p>
                <m>\angle\, ZYX</m> corresponds to <m>\angle\, QPR</m>
            </p>
            
            <p>
                Since <m>\angle\, ZYX=72^\circ</m>, then 
            </p>

            <p>
                <m>\angle\, QPR= 72^\circ </m>
            </p>

            <p>
                 <m>\angle\, YZX</m> corresponds to <m>\angle\, PQR</m>
            </p>

            <p>
                Since <m>\angle\, YZX=61^\circ</m>, then 
            </p>

            <p>
                <m>\angle\, PQR= 61^\circ </m>
            </p>

            <p>
                Now to find the length of <m>PQ</m>, We use the concept of similarity
            </p>

            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>\frac{YZ}{PQ} =\amp\frac{XY}{PR} </mrow>
                    <mrow>\frac{16}{40}= \amp \frac{12}{PR}</mrow>
                    <mrow> PR \times 16= \amp 40 \times 12</mrow>
                    <mrow>PR= \amp \frac{480}{16}</mrow>
                    <mrow>PR= \amp 30\, cm</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
               Triangle <m>ABE</m> is similar to triangle <m>ACD</m>, as shown in the figure below, Given that <m>DC=24\, cm</m> , <m>AE=6\, cm</m><m>ED=12\, cm</m>, determine the length of  <m>BE</m>.
            </p>

            <figure xml:id="tria">
                <caption></caption>
                  <image>
                <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                <latex-image label="tria">
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                         % Define points
                        \coordinate (A) at (0,0);
                        \coordinate (D) at (4,0);
                        \coordinate (C) at (4,3);
                        \coordinate (B) at (2,1.5);
                        \coordinate (E) at (2,0);
                        
                        % Draw shaded triangle in green
                        \fill[green!50] (A) -- (D) -- (C) -- cycle;
                        \draw[thick, green] (A) -- (D) -- (C) -- cycle;
                        
                        % Draw altitude lines with arrows
                        \draw[thick, green, ->] (D) -- (C);
                        \draw[thick, green, ->] (E) -- (B);
                        
                        % Draw straight line from B to E in red
                        \draw[thick, red] (B) -- (E);
                        
                        % Label points
                        \node[below left] at (A) {\textit{A}};
                        \node[below right] at (D) {\textit{D}};
                        \node[above right] at (C) {\textit{C}};
                        \node[above] at (B) {\textit{B}};
                        \node[below] at (E) {\textit{E}};
    
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
            </image>
          </figure>

        </statement>

        <solution>
            <p>
                We first identify the corresponding sides,
            </p>

            <p>
                Side <m>AD</m> corresponds with side <m>AE</m>
            </p>

            <p>
                Side <m>CD</m> corresponds with side <m>BE</m>
            </p>

            <p>
                Side <m>AC</m> corresponds with side <m>AB</m>
            </p>

            <p>
                
                <md>
                    <mrow>\text{By the concept of similarity,} \amp </mrow>
                    <mrow>\frac{DC}{BE} =\frac{AD}{AE}=\frac{AC}{AB}\amp </mrow>
                    <mrow>\text{Given that AE=6 cm, ED=12 cm and DC=24 cm}  \amp </mrow>
                    <mrow>\text{Therefore,}\frac{DC}{BE} =\amp \frac{AD}{AE}</mrow>
                    <mrow> \frac{24}{BE}=\amp \frac{18}{6}</mrow>
                    <mrow>BE= \amp \frac{(24 \times 6)}{18}</mrow>
                    <mrow>= \amp 8\, cm</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    
